xt":"William Hooker Sr."},{"type":"military","related_id":"H00273","link_text":"Gen. Selah Hart","display_label":"commanded the company he guarded Boston with in early 1776"}],"bio":{"display_name":"Seth Stanley","first_name":"Seth","last_name":"Stanley","married_names":[]},"residence":{},"baptism":{},"research_tags":[],"research_sources":[],"documents":[],"naming_inspiration":[],"institutions":[],"landmarks":[],"artworks":[],"quotes":[],"military_service":[{"war":"American Revolutionary War","war_id":"WAR004","rank":"Corporal","rank_start":"Private","rank_end":"Corporal","rank_year_start":1776,"rank_year_end":1776,"unit":"Col. Erastus Wolcott's Regt. (Capt. Selah Hart's 3rd Co.); Gen. Wadsworth's Brigade; Maj. Sheldon's Light Horse (Capt. Daniel Sloper's Co.)","service_years":"January–December 1776","battles":["BTL013","BTL007"],"notes":"1776 campaign across three commands. Winter 1776: guarded besieged Boston about six weeks in Capt. Selah Hart's 3rd Company, Col. Erastus Wolcott's Regiment. Summer 1776: present at the Battle of Long Island (Aug 27) with Gen. James Wadsworth's Brigade and the retreat from New York. Nov 4–Dec 24, 1776: Corporal in Capt. Daniel Sloper's Company, Maj. Sheldon's Regiment of Light Horse, on Washington's retreat through New Jersey. Source: Record of Service of Connecticut Men in the War of the Revolution (1889), pp. 381, 392, 475; Berlin-Peck, Revolutionary War Soldiers of the Town of Berlin."}],"narrative_blocks":[{"number":1,"category":"marriage","header":"Married three times, his last two wives widows","body":"After Ann Hooker died in 1808 he married twice more, both times to widows: Sabra Winchell Stanley, and in 1822 Abigail Hart Smith, herself already twice-widowed. His will, presented in court July 1827, left the farm and stock to his son Seth and the remainder to his daughters Lydia, Nancy, and Amelia."},{"number":2,"category":"military","header":"His whole war fit in one brutal year","body":"Seth's Revolutionary service was cro